WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
It's the 12th of June, I'm Stephanie Cruz of Ellen Lynx and I'm here today in Raider

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:12.160
talking to Mawver Shaw and to Jill Willie. Mawver, just for reference, in which year

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:19.360
were you born? 1938. And Jill? 1951. Thank you. Mawver, can you tell me a little bit

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:24.800
about your family and how you came to be in Raider where you were born? I was born and

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:31.800
I was born and raised in Raider at number nine in the gardens and I was the second daughter of the family.

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:41.800
Your father was? My father was a blacksmith and I'm not sure, I think the man was just a housewife then.

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:50.800
And we lived there for a while and then I think just before the war finished, my father was a

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:59.800
moved from Raider to work at Winds, I'm not sure what it was, something to do with blacksmithing I would imagine.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:06.800
And we were there for a while because my brother was born in an air raid in Newport itself. Oh, right.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:14.800
And then the way he was, my father was working, it was bombed so we came back to Raider.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:24.800
And I think eventually, I don't know, I don't remember where we were at. Just trying to figure it out.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:35.800
Did you move back to Green Gardens? No, we moved back to a place called, I can't think of the name of it now.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:41.800
It'll come. Whereabouts was it?

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:48.800
I'll just up the, what I call the Pounds Lane but I can't think of the name of the farm. It came to me just before you said something.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:57.800
It's gone again now. Anyway, we shared a house there for a little while and then we came back to live in Raider in Penpole.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:04.800
Opposite to the Contaider Arms pub then, you know, the alleyway up to, you know what I mean?

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:06.800
I do Church Street.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:16.800
And then we lived there then until we were allocated the Moratie Green Gardens and that's where I stayed until I got married.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:29.800
And then we got married in 1963, like myself. And then I think it was about, Mark was six months old when we came to live here.

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:40.800
And you've been here ever since? Yeah, he was born in 1965. And then three years later I had Richard and he was born in 1968.

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:46.800
And then I went, eventually went back to the chemist after Richard went to school before.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:58.800
So if we go back a bit, you first started working at the chemists in 1955. And did you have an interview?

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:09.800
Well, no, actually in one respect, yes, but no in another because I worked for one year in Central Stores, which is now the spa.

00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:17.800
She was owned by Gerald Morgan and his family. And I had worked there for a year.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:25.800
And then my sister, who was already working in the chemists before me for one year, was going to teach a trade in college.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:30.800
So T.C. Price very kindly asked her to ask me would I like the job?

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:42.800
Because he thought the work I was doing at Central Stores was too much for a young woman. So that's how I came to work in the chemists.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:48.800
Right, okay. And Jill, your mum worked in the same chemist, didn't she?

00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:55.800
Yes, she did. Not for very long, I don't think. Probably the very late 50s, going into the early 60s.

00:03:55.800 --> 00:04:06.800
I know she left in 62, but she did have a few very happy years working part time, I believe it was, in the chemist shop.

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:11.800
Yes, but not for T.C. Price. It was for E.W. Price.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:15.800
And what do you remember of Jill's mum?

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:21.800
I can't remember. I don't remember your mum that much. I mean, I remember her going, she was a W.I. member, wasn't she?

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:26.800
But I wasn't there, of course, because I was only a teenager then, wasn't I?

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:31.800
So not a time for me to get under the bridge since then.

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:35.800
So what stories do you remember your mum telling, Jill?

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:42.800
Well, I'll have to tell you. I'll start with a funny one anyway. No, perhaps I'd better start with a more serious one, haven't I?

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:48.800
I know she used to talk about the customers that came in and the sort of things they'd ask for.

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:54.800
And they'd seem to go off at a tangent sometimes, you know, not knowing quite what it was that they wanted.

00:04:54.800 --> 00:05:00.800
I think they wanted the assistants there to sort out their problems, you know.

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:08.800
I'm sure a lot of that used to happen. And of course, these are in the days where you didn't sort of walk around and help yourself like a supermarket.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:11.800
You actually went to the counter, didn't you?

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:18.800
And people used to come in with their problems. And I remember one lady, she was a single lady,

00:05:18.800 --> 00:05:23.800
but she obviously thought she was in the family way, which of course was a bit hush hush in those days.

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:32.800
And she went up to my mother asking her if there was anything my mother could do or anything my mother could give her, you know, in these circumstances.

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:37.800
And of course, my poor mother, well, she wasn't in any position to do that sort of thing.

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:40.800
You know, that was a bit of a sad story.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:43.800
Quite hard for her.

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:50.800
Then I remember something rather funny. There was a lady working there, who all the knew very well, called Jean Buffton.

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:58.800
And she had an amazing sense of humour. And one day a customer came into the chemist saying to Jean,

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:04.800
look, can you help me, please? I want something, a nice present for a nice little old lady.

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:09.800
Jean sort of looked at her and said, well, how about a little old man?

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:14.800
I thought that was a lovely story. I still tell that one.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:21.800
And more for you. You've got a little black book there where something's written down in it, haven't you?

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:26.800
Oh, right, yes, we did, yes. We used to have a lot of fun about this. Do you want to read that one?

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:28.800
Yes, I'll read a few.

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:32.800
Oh, really, about myself, because I shouldn't say it ahead of time.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:42.800
Right, it says here. This is myself now over. I went up to the cemetery last night collecting, but I didn't get an answer.

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:47.800
And what did some people come and ask for?

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:55.800
Because as Jill says, you didn't go and have a look on the shelf. You asked for certain kinds of hand cream.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:59.800
That's right, different ones come and ask for different things. Four years one.

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:06.800
Somebody asked for scruples ammonia, and it should have been scrubbed ammonia. We still have that today, don't we?

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:08.800
We do.

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:18.800
Oh, and another one was somebody asked, could they have some J, Jews fluid? Should have been J's fluid.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:20.800
J's fluid, yes, I remember that.

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:26.800
And you were saying just earlier, going through some of the changes that you saw in the shop,

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:32.800
you used to have to handwrite the labels for the medicines that were dispensed.

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:44.800
Yes, we did. Yes, that's quite interesting. You got writers crap doing that, but of course it wasn't as busy as it got eventually, you know, with the NHS.

00:07:44.800 --> 00:08:00.800
And then we sort of progressed. And I think it was after T.C. Price retired, and even when E.W. retired, Mrs. Evans, that was another pharmacist who bought the chemists off E.W.

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:05.800
And she had already bought a chemist off him in Willish. Oh, right.

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:10.800
And like they followed one another really to Rairdham. She actually had retired.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:19.800
But because her son was going to university, she felt she would have to go back to work to see him through university.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:25.800
And then afterwards it didn't matter to much, she said, you know, but she was quite a character.

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:32.800
And I think she had everything under the sun in the chemist then, like, you know, entirely different to E.W. and T.C. Price.

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:40.800
And I can remember this is Kathleen Price now, the previous owner's wife.

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:46.800
She said to me one day, she said, it's like a woe, she said, it's not a chemist shop.

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:48.800
And she was quite sharp about that.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:55.800
So when you first started working at the chemist, can you describe what the shop looked like inside?

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.800
It looked like it would go in through the front doors.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:09:02.800
Well, yeah, well, there's a lot of.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:07.800
At the back of the shop, at the back of the counter in the actual shop,

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:18.800
there were like all these drawers with all these labels on, like mothballs and, you know, varying things all in these little cupboards behind you.

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:24.800
And then there were shelves above with all these carboys and things, you know.

00:09:24.800 --> 00:09:27.800
And I remember one day we had to dust the top shelves.

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:35.800
I can remember T.C. Price saying to me, Maverick, don't take the top off that ammonia because it'll take your head off.

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:38.800
You said if you must have, of course I did, didn't I?

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:40.800
Then you came down the ladder.

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:43.800
I love you.

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:44.800
Thanks, we don't.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:47.800
Yeah. And do you remember the shop as it was like that?

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:54.800
Yes, I do. I remember cupboards full of jars of these very interesting looking medicines.

00:09:54.800 --> 00:10:01.800
I remember that. And I remember there was like a little almost like an ante room which had baby food.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.800
I remember the shelves behind shelves sort of thing.

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.800
And then there was one completely full room baby food.

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:16.800
I remember. And of course, then you had the other things on display, like nice perfumes and nice talcum powders and soaps.

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:21.800
And perhaps something for the little old lady is what that lady I think was really talking about.

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:29.800
Yes, and if I can just mention, my father had a very good friendship with Mr. T.C. Price.

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:39.800
And I remember being literally in the back behind the scenes trying on pairs of glasses with my father and Mr. Price.

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:41.800
Because he was an optometrist as well.

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:42.800
That's right, yeah.

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:49.800
And some of his younger family, you know, we'd get together and try on lipsticks, Dorothy Gray particularly.

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:51.800
We thought we were very, very sophisticated.

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:55.800
But all this was going on sort of behind the scenes as it were.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:11:01.800
I don't remember, for instance, glasses or an awful lot of makeup actually on display.

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:02.800
Yeah, that's right.

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:09.800
Yes, I certainly remember it. And of course, the big difference being that you went up to the counter to...

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:10.800
Yeah, that's right.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:16.800
And T.C. Price used to make concoctions for the farmers.

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:20.800
And he had a lovely, like, what do they call it?

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:25.800
A book that he kept them in, you know, he wrote the recipes in.

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:27.800
Beautiful handwriting he did.

00:11:27.800 --> 00:11:30.800
But I don't know where that chronicle went.

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:32.800
It was certainly in the chemist's...

00:11:32.800 --> 00:11:40.800
After Mrs. Evans left and then Mr. Ken Evans, he came.

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:44.800
No, Edward, sorry, not Evans, sorry. Mr. Edwards came.

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:48.800
And when they left, I think they took it with them.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:50.800
You know, I've got a feeling that they loved it.

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:53.800
It was a shame because you shouldn't have been left really there.

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:56.800
And so that was for the animals?

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:57.800
Yes.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:58.800
Yes.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.800
Well, I'll tell you what it is.

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:02.800
We used to sit out the back.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:08.800
There was like a lean-to at the back and then one sat up like today sort of thing.

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:14.800
And we'd mix this concoction up in a big bucket.

00:12:14.800 --> 00:12:18.800
And if the wind was in the right direction, we would take your breath away.

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:22.800
And it was what we called a green salve.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:27.800
And I remember this one day, saying to Mr. Price, well, what exactly is that for?

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:32.800
Well, it's something they put on the little slabs when they were castrated.

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:35.800
I thought, poor little things.

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:37.800
Do you remember what was in it?

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:41.800
Oh, no. I can't remember now. That's so many years ago.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:43.800
I mean, that stopped a long time ago.

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:45.800
But you have a memory of...

00:12:45.800 --> 00:12:49.800
I do have a memory of the medicines that he used to make.

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:54.800
And there was a couple of things he'd make, which is supposedly to cure a cold.

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:57.800
I think they were like a general antidote, really.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.800
One was pink and one was white.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:03.800
And he claimed that one was vanilla and one was strawberry.

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:05.800
And if you took this, you'd be fixed up.

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:14.800
Well, the taste of these was so absolutely ghastly that the very thought of taking it instantly cured you.

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.800
I'm sure it was psychological.

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:18.800
But I'll never forget those.

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:23.800
And the very thought, you knew he was disappearing out the back to make these concoctions.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:25.800
And I thought, oh, no, here we go.

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:29.800
Oh, gosh. Oh, for goodness sake.

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:31.800
Oh, look, a bottle.

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:33.800
One of the bottles out.

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:35.800
Those were the bottles.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.800
Glass bottle and stopper and...

00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:40.800
A jar.

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:42.800
There's some more there.

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:44.800
Was the green salve kept in that jar?

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:46.800
No, no, no. That was for other things.

00:13:46.800 --> 00:13:48.800
I see.

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:50.800
There's no label on it.

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:52.800
There needs to be a label on it, but there's another small...

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:54.800
Oh, that's a label on that one.

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:56.800
No, there's not been a label.

00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:58.800
Pil-hydra.

00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:00.800
I don't know what that is.

00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:02.800
I mean, that's a pass.

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:04.800
Jill, can you pass me the step up by you there?

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:06.800
The step, certainly.

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:08.800
Just chuck that on the floor.

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:12.800
And the glass bottle is labelled salt-tri-pan blue.

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:17.800
One gram with a squiggle there that I can't...

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:19.800
You need a promise.

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:21.800
Yes, we need a promise.

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:23.800
It's like they used to make up medicines, you know, didn't they?

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:25.800
Absolutely.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:29.800
And notice telephone number 45.

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:31.800
Yeah, but it's... What is it now?

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:35.800
It's probably something similar.

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:37.800
810...

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:41.800
145, perhaps.

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:43.800
It's 445, isn't it?

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:45.800
810-445.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:48.800
And I think it remains so now to this day.

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:50.800
Probably.

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:58.800
Oh, look, more bottles, I remember.

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:00.800
These are all bottles.

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:08.800
Yes, another with a TC Price label on it.

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.800
Raider.

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:12.800
A struggle is out here.

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:14.800
Oh, that's another lovely one.

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:16.800
Spirit of Cantha.

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:22.800
Well, the shape of these bottles, they're absolutely beautiful.

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:24.800
They are, aren't they?

00:15:24.800 --> 00:15:26.800
They're ornamental in themselves now.

00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:28.800
Can I have...

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:30.800
And a blue one.

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:34.800
Now, that one is denoting that that's poisonous, is that right?

00:15:34.800 --> 00:15:36.800
Yes, that's right.

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:38.800
Because it's got...

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:40.800
Well, A, it's got a little bit of a...

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.800
Because it's got...

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:44.800
Well, A, it's got not to be taken...

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:46.800
Blues and browns, you know.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:48.800
Brown, especially, where the poisonous ones.

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:50.800
Mm-hmm.

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:54.800
And the ribbing on the bottles as well, that's...

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:56.800
I don't know if that was...

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:58.800
Yeah, just to show you the difference of the bottles.

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:02.800
I had thought that it was so that you didn't take it by accident at night.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:04.800
Don't look at the dachshund.

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:06.800
So you could feel that it's got that thing on.

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:08.800
And you knew that you shouldn't take it.

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:10.800
Perhaps somebody...

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:12.800
Do you know, I haven't realised I had so many of these left.

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:14.800
Perhaps somebody with poor eyesight.

00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:16.800
Mm-hmm.

00:16:16.800 --> 00:16:18.800
They would rely on the tactile nature.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:20.800
That's the dropper, look.

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:22.800
Yes, gosh, yes.

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:24.800
Eye drops or ear drops, so it could be iodine.

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:26.800
You can't buy iodine today, now, can you?

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.800
I've no idea, haven't tried.

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:32.800
Isn't it betadine that we take now, and it doesn't hurt as much?

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:34.800
Oh, I don't know.

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:36.800
But I remember iodine.

00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:38.800
Ouch.

00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:40.800
Yes, it was quite painful.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.800
The manganate of potash my grandmother used as well.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:44.800
Oh, yes, yeah.

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:46.800
There you go.

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:52.800
So going back to the chemist then, obviously there were quite a lot of changes over your time there.

00:16:52.800 --> 00:16:56.800
We've talked a little bit about labels.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.800
And technology changed quite a lot as well.

00:17:00.800 --> 00:17:02.800
Or maybe, let's go back to...

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:05.800
When you first worked there, did Mr Price have a telephone?

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:07.800
Yes, yes he did.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:10.800
I used to be really nervous of answering it.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:12.800
But he made you do it, you know.

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:15.800
He used to say, you know, you'll get used to it, and you did.

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:21.800
And did people ring up to say that there'd been an emergency or an accident or something?

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:24.800
No, I don't remember much about that.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:26.800
I don't think so.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:29.800
I don't really, we used to deal with oxygen.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:31.800
Being oxygen-cylinders.

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:34.800
And if somebody needed oxygen at home,

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:40.800
T.C. Price would connect it up and, you know, take it forward to get it delivered to them.

